<h2>Memory Types and Their Risk Levels</h2>

<div class="threat-card medium">
  <h4>Context Window (Session Memory)</h4>
  <p>Information the agent holds within a single conversation. A prompt injection can plant false context for the rest of the session. Risk is bounded — it clears when the session ends.</p>
</div>

<div class="threat-card">
  <h4>External Vector Database (Persistent Memory)</h4>
  <p>Documents and notes stored externally and retrieved when relevant. If an attacker writes to this store, the poisoning persists indefinitely and affects every future query. Highest risk memory type.</p>
</div>

<div class="threat-card high">
  <h4>Interaction History (Episodic Memory)</h4>
  <p>Records of previous conversations that shape future behavior. If interaction records can be fabricated or tampered with, the agent's learned patterns can be manipulated. Particularly dangerous in agents that adapt to feedback.</p>
</div>

<StepWalkthrough
