<div class="defense-section">
  <h3>Memory Security Controls</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Isolate memory per user where possible.</strong> Shared memory is highest risk. Separate memory spaces limit the blast radius of any single poisoning event.</li>
    <li><strong>Control write access to memory stores.</strong> Not every agent interaction should write to shared persistent memory. Treat memory writes with the same access control rigor as database writes.</li>
    <li><strong>Track memory provenance.</strong> Each memory record should carry metadata: when created, what interaction created it, who was involved. Essential for forensic investigation.</li>
    <li><strong>Implement memory expiry.</strong> Old memory records should expire or require revalidation. This limits how long poisoned content can influence behavior.</li>
    <li><strong>Human review for high-stakes memories.</strong> If agent memory influences significant decisions — competitive strategy, regulatory guidance, customer risk — those records require human review before becoming trusted reference material.</li>
  </ol>
</div>

